# KlaroPH Production Rules

## Core Engineering Principle

Always use **replacement-first engineering**.

When introducing a new implementation:

* remove obsolete code immediately
* do not layer new logic on top of old logic
* do not preserve dead wrappers, stale imports, or duplicate selectors

---

## Mandatory Rule for Every Change

Before completing any edit, check what became obsolete because of the change.

Always remove:

* unused imports
* dead JSX blocks
* obsolete props
* stale state
* abandoned wrappers
* duplicate CSS selectors
* old helper functions no longer used

---

## Layout Discipline

When changing UI:

1. Inspect parent wrappers before patching child components

2. Prefer root-cause fixes over padding hacks

3. Avoid adding override layers if structure can solve it

4. One layout owner only:

   * parent OR card OR content
   * never all three

5. Remove replaced layout rules immediately

Never leave:

* old flex logic beside new grid logic
* duplicate card height systems
* conflicting min-height rules

---

## CSS Discipline

Before adding CSS:

1. Check if an older selector already owns that responsibility
2. Replace instead of override whenever possible
3. Avoid duplicate selector blocks
4. Remove selector groups tied to removed components

Never keep:

* dead dashboard selectors
* legacy responsive patches
* grouped selectors for unrelated cards

Every CSS change must leave the file cleaner.

---

## Component Discipline

When editing components:

1. Remove dead branches immediately
2. Remove unused state immediately
3. Remove stale useEffect logic immediately
4. Remove old props if replaced

Never leave:

* parallel rendering paths
* retired modals still imported
* abandoned helper wrappers

---

## Dashboard Rules

Dashboard is production-sensitive.

When editing dashboard:

* preserve visual rhythm
* preserve spacing system
* inspect wrapper ownership first
* avoid local fixes that create future CSS fights

Cards must be:

* content-driven
* structurally clean
* independently understandable

---

## File Hygiene

If a file becomes unused:

* mark for deletion immediately
* confirm reference trace
* remove related selectors

Never keep dead files after confirmed replacement.

---

## Before Completing Any Task

Always report:

A. What changed
B. What obsolete code was removed
C. What remains intentionally active

---

## Production Priority

Stability is more important than cleverness.

If two solutions work:
choose the one with:

* fewer layers
* fewer overrides
* fewer hidden dependencies

---

## KlaroPH Standard

Every accepted change must leave the surrounding file cleaner than before.
